      "message": "\u003e I\u0027d like to propose a general workflow which I\u0027m hoping we can standardize on:\n\u003e 1. Every app/service has a kubernetes YAML file template checked into buildbot.git.\n\u003e 2. Every instance of an app/service has a JSON config file which specifies things like CPUs, memory, disk sizes, etc, also checked into buildbot.git (or an internal repo where required).\n\u003e 3. pushk either absorbs the functionality of or shells out to kube-conf-gen to regenerate the relevant YAML files in the config repo using the YAML templates and JSON configs from above, plus the new image names.  Having this functionality inside pushk is required because pushk (correctly) expects a clean checkout.\n\n\n+1 for coming up with a common flow for these more complex apps, but only if this flow is optional, there are a lot of apps (docserverk, dot, hashtag, alert-manager, fiddle, grafana, etc.) for which that flow would be overkill.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e With the above, we should never need to review changes to the config repo, even for new apps.  I\u0027m not sure how the flags to pushk would work; kube-conf-gen uses -t and -c for the YAML template and JSON config, respectively.  Ideally, it\u0027d be nice to be able to provide a regex and update all matching apps.  I\u0027d also like to be able to update multiple apps in one shot, eg. adding an autoroller requires creating the backend and updating the frontend to be aware of it.\n\u003e \n\u003e Context: I never use pushk, for the following reasons:\n\u003e - I almost never want to push all 72 rollers.  The only exception would be sweeping changes that affect most/all of them.\n\u003e - /tmp/*-config is always dirty, corrupted, or missing altogether.  pushk nearly always fails on my machine because of this, so when I do use it, I have to go verify that those checkouts are clean (and typically recreate) so it\u0027s easier just to hand-edit the files I want.\n\nThis CL adds and env variable that allows you